<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="use-case-mapping">
  <metadata>
    <tier>solo</tier>
    <group>research</group>
    <domain>researcher</domain>
    <summary>Document specific ways users interact with your product via actors, goals, preconditions, main flows and alternative flows.</summary>
    <category>research</category>
    <difficulty>beginner</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-26</created>
    <tags>
      <tag>research</tag>
      <tag>use-cases</tag>
      <tag>requirements</tag>
      <tag>user-flows</tag>
      <tag>specifications</tag>
    </tags>
  </metadata>

  <content>
    <title>Use Case Mapping</title>

    <summary>Products get built without clear understanding of how users will actually use them. Features become disconnected from real workflows, critical paths are missed, edge cases overlooked until production, and teams lack shared understanding. Use case mapping documents specific ways users interact with your product to achieve goals. It answers: What exactly will users do with this? By defining actors, goals, preconditions, main flows, alternatives, and postconditions, you create a shared understanding across business, engineering, and QA.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>The root cause of disconnected features is having no documented mapping between user goals and system behavior. Use case mapping translates validated user research into specifications engineers can build from. It creates a shared model across business, engineering, and QA of what users actually do. It ensures alternative flows and edge cases are explicit before they cause production incidents. In compliance or regulated domains, it becomes mandatory documentation that shows all paths have been considered.</p>
      <p>Use cases are living documentation that evolve as the system evolves. They serve as traceability tissue connecting tests, stories, designs, and analytics events back to user intent. A use case at the user-goal level balances detail with agility. At the user-goal level (not subfunctional detail), a use case stays maintainable and relevant as the product changes.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Translating validated user research into specifications engineering can build from.</item>
        <item>Drafting acceptance criteria when stories are too thin and edge cases are missed in production.</item>
        <item>Cross-team alignment: business, engineering, and QA need a shared model of what users do and what the system must support.</item>
        <item>Compliance or regulated domains where alternative flows must be explicit and documented.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Pre-discovery: writing use cases before validating problem produces fiction and wastes effort.</item>
        <item>For purely internal scripts or dev tooling where the overhead of documentation exceeds the benefit.</item>
        <item>For exploratory prototyping where requirements are intentionally fuzzy and changing daily.</item>
        <item>When the team uses Jobs-to-Be-Done plus user-story-mapping already; pick one model, not three competing frameworks.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="use-case-components">
      <p>A complete use case has six essential elements that together describe what a user needs to accomplish and how the system supports them. Actor (who performs the action): Identifies the user or external system initiating the interaction. Examples: Freelancer, Admin, Moderator, Guest. Goal (what they want to achieve): The outcome the actor is trying to reach in a single session. Examples: Create an invoice, approve a request, reset password, add a team member. Preconditions (what must be true before): The state the system must be in for this use case to start. Examples: User is logged in, account has a payment method on file, at least one client exists in system. Main Flow (happy path steps in order): Numbered steps alternating between actor action and system response. Example: 1. Actor clicks button. 2. System displays form. 3. Actor enters data. 4. System validates and saves. Alternative Flows (variations when things don't go smoothly): Branch or exception scenarios. Examples: If payment fails then..., if user lacks permission then..., if record already exists then.... Postconditions (result when complete): The state of the system and user after successful completion. Examples: Invoice sent to customer, record appears in sent list, confirmation email received, payment link active.</p>
    </section>

    <section name="actor-identification">
      <p>Begin by identifying all actors who interact with the system. Actor types vary in scope and relationship to the system. Primary actors are the main beneficiaries who use the system to achieve their goal. Examples: customer, user, freelancer, buyer, seller, operator. Secondary actors support the primary actor or the system. Examples: admin, moderator, manager, support agent, accountant. External actors are system-to-system interactions outside your control. Examples: payment gateway, email service API, third-party accounting integration, SMS provider, shipping carrier.</p>

      <p>Questions to identify actors systematically: Who will use this system directly? Who benefits from it, directly or indirectly? Who administers or maintains it? What external systems or services interact with it? What third-party integrations exist? Are there different roles based on permissions (free user, paying customer, admin, moderator)? Do new users have different flows than returning users? Are there different actor workflows based on geography, organization type, or use frequency? Should you model team admin separately from individual user? What about super admin or support access?</p>
    </section>

    <section name="goal-listing">
      <p>For each actor, identify their goals. Goals operate at different levels and understanding which level is critical for staying focused. Summary level goals are high-level business objectives that span many sessions (Manage business finances, run a marketplace, help customers succeed). User level goals are what someone accomplishes in a single session or interaction (Create invoice for client, review seller metrics, onboard new team member). Subfunction level goals are sub-steps within a session goal (Add line item to invoice, edit seller address, select payment method). Stay primarily at user level goals. Sub-function level is too detailed and changes with UI. Summary level is too vague.</p>

      <p>For each actor, list: Primary goals (what they do most often, or what is most valuable to the business). Secondary goals (nice to have but not essential). For example, a Freelancer's primary goals are: Create and send invoices, track payments received, manage client information. Secondary goals: Generate reports for accounting, customize invoice templates, integrate with accounting software, track time spent on projects. Bonus goals: Collaborate with team members, outsource work. Explicitly prioritizing lets engineering focus on what matters most first.</p>
    </section>

    <section name="main-flow-mapping">
      <p>For each use case, document the happy path in Actor/System step format. Use Case name. Actor (who). Goal (what they want). Preconditions (what must be true). Main Flow (numbered steps). Postconditions (result when successful).</p>

      <code lang="text"><![CDATA[
Use Case: Create Invoice
Actor: Freelancer
Goal: Create and send invoice to client

Preconditions:
- User is logged in
- At least one client exists

Main Flow:
1. Freelancer clicks "New Invoice"
2. System shows invoice form with auto-number
3. Freelancer selects client from dropdown
4. System populates client details
5. Freelancer adds line items
6. System calculates subtotal and tax
7. Freelancer sets due date
8. Freelancer clicks Send
9. System sends invoice to client email

Postconditions:
- Invoice sent to client
- Invoice appears in Sent list
- Payment link in email
      ]]></code>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Main flows must stay at user-goal level. Limit to 10 steps maximum. If longer, split into sub-use-cases. Write actor steps first, system response second to keep flow actor-centric.</statement>
        <rationale>User-goal level keeps documentation readable and maintainable. Too much detail about screens and buttons locks the design too early. Actor-first perspective ensures the documentation serves users, not just systems.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="alternative-flow-identification">
      <p>Alternative flows capture variations, branches, and error handling that real users encounter. There are three types. Extension alternatives add optional steps or variations to the main flow (If user wants draft instead of sending, save draft). Exception alternatives handle errors and failures (If email invalid, show validation error and let user retry). Branch alternatives offer genuinely different paths based on conditions (If recurring invoice, offer schedule option, if one-time offer immediate send).</p>

      <p>Example alternatives for Create Invoice use case: 2a. Client doesn't exist yet (branch): Instead of selecting from dropdown, freelancer creates new client inline, system saves client and returns to step 4 to populate. 3a. Email validation fails (exception): System detects invalid email format, shows specific error message, freelancer corrects and resubmits. 7a. Save as draft instead of sending (extension): Freelancer clicks Save Draft instead of Send, invoice saved with draft status, no email sent, use case ends without postconditions. 8a. Payment declined (exception): Payment gateway rejects card, system shows error, transaction rolls back, use case fails.</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Prioritize alternatives by production likelihood and user impact, not edge-case completeness. Aim for 3 to 5 alternatives per main flow, sorted by frequency of occurrence and severity of impact.</statement>
        <rationale>Exhaustive enumeration leads to document bloat and analysis paralysis. Focus on what actually happens in production with real users. Estimate frequency from interviews, analytics, or support tickets if available. Leave theoretical edge cases for later or as notes.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="common-mistakes">
      <p>Too vague: Saying system validates instead of specifying what validation. Fix: Be specific about each step. Missing alternatives: Assuming happy path only. Fix: Always document error cases. System-centric: Using system perspective instead of user perspective. Fix: Write from actor's perspective. Too detailed: Describing every button and field. Fix: Stay at user goal level. No preconditions: Skipping what must be true first. Fix: Always state preconditions. Skipping validation: Not checking with actual users. Fix: Review with real users.</p>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Use cases drift from reality if not maintained alongside code. Unmaintained docs become fiction.</description>
        <reason>Treat them as living docs, updated when code changes. Outdated use cases mislead new team members.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Over-specification kills agility. Too much detail about screens locks design too early.</description>
        <reason>Keep at user-goal level by default. Subfunctional detail prevents responsive design changes.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>System actor abstraction confuses agents. They invent system agency where there is none.</description>
        <reason>Enforce actor-first perspective in prompts. Require actor to initiate, system to respond.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="agentic-workflow">
      <p>Pipeline: extract actors and goals from interviews, draft main flows, enumerate alternatives, cross-link to tests. Agents are good at templating use cases from research and suggesting missed alternatives. Agents are bad at picking granularity level. Keep humans in level decisions.</p>

      <p>Recommended subagents: actor-extractor (haiku) pulls actors from interviews and persona docs. flow-drafter (sonnet) generates main success scenarios. alt-flow-enumerator (sonnet) proposes alternatives. test-linker (haiku) maps steps to test IDs. faion-sdd-executor-agent pushes use cases through spec to design to test-plan lifecycle.</p>

      <code lang="text"><![CDATA[
Role: flow-drafter.
Input: actor name, goal description, validated pains, current solutions.
Output JSON: use_case_id, actor, level, preconditions array, main_flow array (each step has who and action), postconditions array.
Rule: max 10 steps main flow. Write actor steps first, system response second.
      ]]></code>

      <code lang="text"><![CDATA[
Role: alt-flow-enumerator.
Input: main_flow JSON from flow-drafter.
Task: propose alternatives for validation and error cases.
Output JSON: alts array with trigger_step, type (extension|exception|branch), flow array.
Constraint: max 5 alts. Sort by production likelihood.
      ]]></code>
    </section>

    <section name="best-practices">
      <list>
        <item>Use case ID is connective tissue. Link tests, stories, designs, analytics events back to UC-XXX. Traceability is how you prevent duplicate work and catch gaps.</item>
        <item>Write actor actions first, system responses second. This keeps the documentation actor-centric. Agents naturally invert this and the docs read system-centric instead of user-centric; enforce actor-first in all prompts.</item>
        <item>Stay at user-goal level by default. Drop to subfunction only for safety-critical or compliance flows. Subfunctional detail locks design too early and rots as UI evolves.</item>
        <item>Prioritize alternatives by production likelihood, not by edge-case completeness. Perfectionism and exhaustive enumeration waste review cycles.</item>
        <item>Cross-link related use cases (Includes, Extends, Related) but avoid deep hierarchies. Three levels maximum. Deeper hierarchies become unmaintainable.</item>
        <item>Pair every use case with Definition of Ready review with engineering before sprint entry. Engineering should sign off that a use case is clear enough to spec from.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="ai-agent-gotchas">
      <list>
        <item>LLMs over-decompose into subfunctions. Explicitly cap step count (e.g., max 10).</item>
        <item>Agents invent preconditions not validated ("user has API key"). Require citations from interviews.</item>
        <item>System validates X is most-fabricated. Require validation rules from business rules document.</item>
        <item>Postconditions skipped under token pressure. Add self-check that postconditions length greater than 0.</item>
        <item>Cross-flow consistency lost across re-generations. Keep a registry file of IDs.</item>
        <item>Human-in-loop checkpoints: actor plus goal sign-off, level decision, alt-flow trim.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

